<dl id="un3031g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un3" href="#un3031">UN3: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un3all.htm#un3031g"> (VIII.A.5) 31(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Tantalus (old) <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un3031g"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/lexf.htm#un3031g">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/f86.htm#un3031g">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/f86.htm#un3031g">1986 (6.229)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/l22f.htm#un3031g">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un3031g">MS Ros-10</ms> </li><li><a name="f12d" href="../udra/u6da.htm#f12d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/f/f12d.htm#un3031g">Draft: 6.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Moreover I beheld <mark>Tantalus</mark> in grievous torment, standing in a mere and the water came nigh unto his chin. And he stood straining as one athirst, but he might not attain to the water to drink of it. For often as <mark>that old man</mark> stooped down in his eagerness to drink, so often the water was swallowed up and it vanished away, and the black earth still showed at his feet, for some god parched it evermore. <small> Homer, <a name="OHBL" href="/udra/udex.htm#ohbl"><cite title="source">The Odyssey</cite></a>, trans. Butcher &amp; Lang (1906), 190</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In <i>Ulysses</i> episode &ldquo;Hades&rdquo;: the dullgarbed old man. </mm> </dd></dl>
